review_blob: Nice dark brown with a substantial, quickly thinning tan head. Smells of oak, vanilla, dark malts, with just a hint of something sour. Smells great. Taste is roasted malts, coffee, and a very subtle hint of bourbon. Mouthfeel is lightly carbonated and easy drinking. Overall this is just a well balanced porter. The barrel aging barely comes through, but the little that it does is a nice added touch to a very solid beer.

Dark black with tan head. Smells of dark malts, chocolate, vanilla and wood. Taste is coffee, malt, chocolate and a hint of bourbon. A bit more carbonated than lots of stouts. Perfectly fine, but Im probably not going to go back again.
beer_name: Backwoods Ridge Run Stout - Bourbon Barrel

review_blob: Its a dark amber color with just a smidgen of foam. Smells dominantly of its roasted malt. Taste is the same. Medium bodied with about as much carbonation as youd expect. All in all, kind of boring and one not.
Pours a murky gold with some head. Smells of orange and maybe coriander. Taste follows the nose. Very smooth with little carbonation. Drinkable, but uninspired.

Pours jet black with a thin brown head. Wonderful smell with a big, boozy scent. Lots of roasted malts, oak, and cognac. Taste is lots of malt, oak, some caramel, and a lot of cognac and spice. Mouthfeel is great, full and smooth. Overall its complex and good - not great. Though with some time in the cellar it might become something sorbitan

Pours dark espresso brown. Has a thin brown head. Smells booze forward, strong notes of vanilla. Some cherries, oak, and spice from the rye. Tastes of wood, cherries, and licorice paired with the warming spice of rye. Only real complaint is it feels a little on the thin side. A wonderful variation on a wonderful base beer.

2013 batch on draft.

Pours inky black with a tan head. Smells of coffee with hints of oak and bourbon. Taste is coffee, chocolate, wood, caramel, with hints of vanilla and alcohol. Incredibly well balanced, you dont feel its strength when drinking. Feels very silky and smooth on the way down. A great stout.

Tried the Nitro version.

Pours a golden brown with a foamy white head that lingers in the glass. Smells vaguely of hops and malt.

Taste is similar. Hints of malt and hops briefly visit but are fleeting and quickly fade away, replaced with bland mildness. Drinks very smoothly with very light carbonation. 

Nitrogen certainly didnt help this beer.

A murky, dark red color. Very little head. Smells of grapes. Tastes as sour as expected. Lightly funkified, slight hints of agave. Wine presence became more pronounced as it warmed. Finishes crisp and dry. An interesting beer.

Pours bright gold yellow with small white had. Strong citrus hops smell. Taste is very floral cut with light biscuit-like malt. Lots of grapefruit. Nicely crisp in the mouth. Easily drinkable and a nice choice come summer.

Dark with little carbonation. Smells vaguely of root beer. Feels syrupy. Tastes overly sweet and of artificial root beer flavoring added to a cheap malt beverage.

After having tried Not Your Fathers Root Best and thinking it was okay this drastically missed the mark. I poured out my bottle half way through.

Pours into a copper, cloudy liquid. It smells heavily of a variety of fruit. Taste is more of the same. The fruit flavor is kind of muddled together but maybe banana is most pronounced. There is also a hint of wine acidity, but otherwise the barrels dont really come through. Slight carbonation and guess down smoothly. All in all its a decent beer but not necessarily worth the price tag.
Drinking a 2014 bottle. Pours a nice cloudy brown. Smells sweet and of dried fruit. Tastes plum, raisin, caramel, and fig. It drinks lightly carbonated and silky smooth. Quite good.

Drinking the 2008 vintage. Light bodied, smells of cherries. The aging mellowed the tartness leaving a lot earthy, wine-like complexity. It has an excellent finish and is completely worthy of the praise it receives.
